	abstract = {Early socio-cognitive conceptions of self-regulated learning (SRL) emphasized individual, cognitive-constructive aspects involved in cognition, behavior, and motivation, as well as social context as a component in the triadic process of self-regulation. More recently, situated perspectives of learning have extended theories and models of self-regulation to highly interactive and dynamic learning situations where shared knowledge construction and collaboration emerge. Self-regulated learning became a cornerstone for exploring more social forms of regulation such as co-regulation and shared regulation. This chapter revisits and updates our earlier conceptualizations of social modes of regulation in collaboration with the aim of: (a) summarizing relevant theoretical ideas, (b) grounding these constructs in their educational psychology foundations, (c) highlighting contemporary research evidence bearing on these ideas, (d) offering directions for future research, and (e) discussing implications for practice. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)},
