	abstract = {This chapter uses a co-regulation of learning framework to help us understand some of the relationships between classroom context and cognition and motivation. It describes aspects of some of those sources that affect learning in the classroom, specifically: the amount and nature of privacy in the classroom, issues of power and trust, issues of diversity and equity, the amount and nature of collaborative work, and the amount and nature of peer assessment and self-assessment in the classroom. Self-regulation of learning is processes students engage in as they set learning goals, implement strategies to reach those goals, monitor and assess their progress toward those goals, establish a productive learning environment, and maintain a sense of self-efficacy. The formative assessment strategy, yielding information about a students thinking in relation to a learning goal, can support both internal and external regulation of learning. Strijbos reviews the panorama of literature on assessment of collaborative learning, identifying many strengths and weaknesses with existing practices.},
